	a <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Ontology> ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> """CERTra hyperactivity: uncontrolled CER transfer out of ER as a result (a) reduced Cer in ER relaxes homeostatic inhibition of SPT results in increase of de novo SL synthesis.
(b) reduced Cer in Golgi  impaires GSL production
(c) excessive CERT activity likely compete with Cer desaturase  at the ER as a result transfer dhCer to trans-Golgi and production of dhSM."""^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , """Disruption of CERT Regulation by Mutations
◦
CerTra-associated CERT1 mutations generally disturb CERT regulation and promote its association with membranes, rather than its normal cytosolic distribution upon inactivation.
◦
These mutations reduce the pool of hyperphosphorylated/inactive CERT by influencing the CERT phosphorylation cycle, which depends on the consecutive actions of PKD, CSNK1G2, and PP2Cε.
◦
Mutations in the SRR (cluster 1), such as p.S132, p.S135, p.S138, and p.S141, directly impair CERT-inactivating phosphorylation.
◦
Mutations in the Central Core Domain (CCD) (clusters 2 and 3), such as p.T166A and p.G243R, affect CERT regulation downstream of PKD phosphorylation. These mutations hinder the conformational change that normally follows phosphorylation.
▪
The CCD, a previously uncharacterized dimeric helical domain, is essential for CERT's autoregulation and sphingolipid homeostasis.
▪
Specifically, p.T166A decreases the helicity and destabilizes the H1 helix within the CCD, while p.G243R primarily impairs CCD dynamics and potentially its interactions with other proteins, rather than affecting its structure.
◦
This impaired autoregulation leads to CERT remaining in an abnormally activated state, where it continuously transfers ceramide"""^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> ;
	<http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title> "mutant CERT1 Certra syndrome (Human) Recon4IMD"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> ;
	<http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/contributor> "https://orcid.org/0009-0002-7487-1936"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> ;
	<http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/date> "2026-06-08"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> .

